 <font face="Arial">
  <hr align="left" color="#000000" size="1"/>
  <p>
   In ASL to talk about a body part you generally just point to it 
			or spell it.
  </p>
  <p>
   <br/>
  </p>
  <p>
   To sign "ARM" you can either just spell it, or you can use the dominant 
	flat hand ("b hand") to show the length of the non-dominant
  arm. The tips of your fingers brush along the upper-inside edge of your
  non-dominant arm from the lower bicep to the wrist.
   <br/>
   <br/>
   ARM:
   <br/>
   <img border="0" height="219" src="/images/arm1.jpg" width="211"/>
   <img border="0" height="219" src="/images/arm2.jpg" width="211"/>
   <img border="0" height="219" src="/images/arm3.jpg" width="211"/>
   <br/>
  </p>
  <hr align="left" color="#000000" size="1"/>
  <p>
   <br/>
   HANDS:
  </p>
  <p>
   This sign looks sort of as if you are cutting off your hands at the
  wrists.    Use the pinkie-edge of the right b hand to
  "slice off" the left hand.  Then use the left b-hand to slice
  off the right hand.  (I know that sounds gross, but at least you will
  remember the sign eh?)
   <br/>
   <br/>
   <img border="0" height="218" src="/images/hands1.jpg" width="205"/>
   <img border="0" height="218" src="/images/hands2.jpg" width="205"/>
   <img border="0" height="218" src="/images/hands3.jpg" width="205"/>
   <img border="0" height="218" src="/images/hands4.jpg" width="205"/>
   <img border="0" height="218" src="/images/hands5.jpg" width="205"/>
   <br/>
  </p>
  <hr align="left" color="#000000" size="1"/>
  <p>
   <br/>
   HEAD:
   <br/>
   Touch the upper part of your head then touch down near your chin.
  </p>
  <p>
   Note the bend at my large knuckles.
   <br/>
   <br/>
   <img border="0" height="230" src="/images/head1.jpg" width="221"/>
   <img border="0" height="230" src="/images/head2.jpg" width="221"/>
   <br/>
  </p>
  <hr align="left" color="#000000" size="1"/>
  <p>
   <br/>
   To express the concept of "leg" I recommend you just spell L-E-G.
   <br/>
   Another way to indicate "leg" is to simply point to your leg.
   <br/>
   Another way is to use your left and right "b hands (closed flat
  hands)" to show the leg.
   <br/>
   <br/>
   LEG:
